5 "§ 120-4.65. Open meetings and public records.
6 The Commission shall be subject to the Chapter 132 of the General Statutes and Article 33C
7 of Chapter 143 of the General Statutes, except to the extent those enactments conflict with the
8 below requirements:
9 (1) Members of the Commission and staff shall not discuss the business of the
10 Commission outside of public meetings.
11 (2) If a member of the Commission violates subdivision (1) of this section, he or
12 she shall place in the public records of the Commission (i) any violating
13 written communication and (ii) a written description of any violating oral
14 communication. The written description of an oral communication must
15 include the name of the parties to the communication, the date and
16 approximate time of the communication, and a description of the nature and
17 substance of the communication.
18 (3) The Commission shall provide at least 14 days' notice prior to any meeting in
19 which votes will be taken.
20 (4) All public meetings must be live-streamed and minutes from the meetings
21 must be made available to the public.
22 "§ 120-4.70. Redistricting criteria.
23 All plans shall meet the following goals, in order of priority:
24 (1) Each identified representative shall represent a single district. The population
25 for a legislative district shall be within five percent (5%) of the ideal
26 population for that district. Congressional districts shall each have a
27 population that is as nearly equal as practicable to the ideal population but in
28 all cases within one-tenth of one percent (0.1%) of the ideal population for
29 that district.
30 (2) Compliance with the North Carolina Constitution, State law, the Constitution
31 of the United States, including the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth
32 Amendment, and federal law to ensure that all persons, including racial and
33 language minorities, have an equal opportunity to elect representatives of their
34 choice. A plan shall not diminish or dilute the ability of a member of a
35 minority from electing a candidate of his or her choice, whether alone or in
36 coalition with others.
37 (3) All districts shall be geographically cohesive and contiguous. Areas that are
38 logically connected to form a unified community, yet are physically separated,
39 are considered cohesive. Areas that are physically adjacent are contiguous.
40 Areas that meet only at the points of adjoining corners are not contiguous.
41 (4) Districts shall respect the integrity of communities of interest to the extent
42 practicable.
43 (5) Districts shall not split precincts and shall respect the geographic integrity of
44 political subdivision boundaries, except to the extent necessary to comply with
45 the preceding criteria.
46 (6) Districts shall not be drawn to favor or discriminate against a political party.
47 Partisan considerations and election results data shall not be used in the
48 drawing of districts in Congressional, House, and Senate plans. No
49 redistricting plan shall diminish or dilute any individual's vote on the basis of
50 party affiliation.
Page 8 DRS15284-BKye-1

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (7) Districts shall not be drawn to favor or discriminate against an incumbent or
2 candidate for office.
3 (8) Splitting of counties shall be minimized and avoided where possible.
4 However, spitting counties is permissible when in constitutional compliance
5 with any required clustering of counties.
6 "§ 120-4.75. Adoption of redistricting plans by the Commission.
7 (a) Integrity and Procedure. – It is the intent of the General Assembly that the
8 Commission conduct itself with integrity and fairness in the creation and adoption of plans. In
9 furtherance of that goal, the Commission shall adopt preliminary, proposed, alternative, and final
10 plans by a vote of at least nine members composed of at least three members appointed to the
11 Commission from each sub-sub-subdivision of G.S. 120-4.55(c)(5)b.
12 (b) Special Masters. – At the beginning of the redistricting cycle, the State Ethics
13 Commission shall submit to the Commission a list of names of persons with an expertise in
14 redistricting who are qualified to serve as a special master. In the event a plan cannot be adopted
15 pursuant to subsection (a) of this section, the Commission shall appoint two special masters from
16 the list of names provided by the State Ethics Commission. The special masters shall be appointed
17 by a vote of at least nine members composed of at least three members appointed to the
18 Commission from each sub-sub-subdivision of G.S. 120-4.55(c)(5)b. A special master appointed
19 pursuant to this subsection shall meet the following criteria:
20 (1) Meet eligibility requirements for applications for membership on the
21 Commission pursuant to G.S. 120-4.55(b).
22 (2) Have a resume that does not reflect a history of working exclusively with one
23 political party or ideology.
24 (c) Adoption by Special Masters. – Any special masters appointed pursuant to this section
25 shall draw a plan and submit the plan, along with the rationale for the plan, to the Commission,
26 which shall adopt that plan, in accordance with the following:
27 (1) Plans proposed by the special masters shall conform to all redistricting criteria
28 in G.S. 120-4.70.
29 (2) Produce one map for any plan.
30 (3) Hold at least four public hearings after producing the map, two of which shall
31 occur in each metropolitan and micropolitan statistical area. Public hearings
32 shall be live-streamed with the ability for citizens to participate virtually.
33 (4) Provide a written evaluation for any plan in accordance with
34 G.S. 120-4.80(b)(6).
35 "§ 120-4.80. Public input.
36 (a) Public Hearings. – It is the intent of the General Assembly that the Commission
37 conduct an open and transparent process enabling full public consideration of and comment on
38 the drawing of plans. In furtherance of that goal, the Commission shall hold public hearings as
39 soon as reasonably practicable after its formation and shall set a timeline for this process; the
40 timeline may be adjusted as needed. The Commission shall engage in a minimum of 20 public
41 hearings across the State. At least one public hearing shall occur in each metropolitan statistical
42 area and at least five public hearings shall occur in the various micropolitan areas. Of those public
43 hearings, at least 10 hearings shall occur before a preliminary plan is released to the public and
44 at least 10 hearings shall occur after a preliminary plan is released to the public but before a
45 proposed or alternative plan is released to the public. All public hearings shall be live-streamed
46 with the ability for citizens to participate virtually.
47 (b) Public Input. – To the extent possible, the Commission shall facilitate the ability of
48 members of the public to provide substantive comments on any plan released to the public. To
49 achieve that goal, the Commission shall provide members of the public with all of the following
50 resources:
DRS15284-BKye-1 Page 9

